I'm assuming our framebox code doesn't run on live, and its intent is to emulate live.

This builds on top of https://github.com/google/WebFundamentals/pull/3579 and adds a `sandbox` attribute. This means the iframe runs on a different origin, more like it does on live.

pull_request_body: I've made it up to `dom-order-matters.md` in the Focus section. Still got a ways to go. I'm doing a ton of editing and cleanup\n
petele_changes_requested_str:
Lots of good content here, overall it looks good. I've left a bunch of specific comments throughout. One general comment is that I'd like to see more images. Some pages feel like big walls of text.

Some general comments (called out in some places but need to be fixed across all files):
- Remove `{# wf_review_required #}` tags
- Update `{# wf_updated_on #}` and `{# wf_published_on #}` to more recent dates
- Place images inline using `attempt-left` or `attempt-right`
- Nit - Preference for Markdown syntax over HTML (hyperlinks)
- Use Warning/Note/etc markdown syntax instead of HTML/Aside
- Line breaks at 80 chars
- Avoid `target="_blank"` where possible, 
- Use `class="external"` on external hyperlinks where it makes sense
- `framebox` is are only required for JavaScript, simple html samples don't need it. You can optionally use it if you want specific styles 
- Avoid `code wrap` instead, use 4 spaces.

pull_request_body: @petele I've double-checked this for other macros.\n
R: @petele @arthurevans @jpmedley \n

I've changed the examples to use `srcObject`, which is widely implemented now.

Couple of nitpicks: the `capture` attribute is boolean, and the stream object from a `getUserMediaI()` call is a `MediaStream`.

A few other suggestions below.
- Maybe add catch clauses?
- Might be worth mentioning the video option for the <input> method, i.e: 

`<input type="file" accept="video/*" capture />`
- Maybe mention that you can set the canvas dimensions from videoWidth and videoHeight — and it's probably better to set the canvas dimensions in JavaScript rather than in the HTML.
- With the examples (e.g. upload and image on a canvas to a server) I wonder if it would be worth adding how-to suggestions?
- You might want to link to samples:
  - [simpl.info/mediacapture](http://simpl.info/mediacapture/)
  - [webrtc.github.io/samples/src/content/getusermedia/gum](https://webrtc.github.io/samples/src/content/getusermedia/gum/)
  - [webrtc.github.io/samples/src/content/getusermedia/canvas](https://webrtc.github.io/samples/src/content/getusermedia/canvas/)

pull_request_title: Update images for "Avoiding the Not Secure Warning in Chrome".

pull_request_body:
To find unused images I ran:

```sh
#!/bin/bash

# Execute this from /src/content/en/tools/chrome-devtools

function search {
  # Provides just the filename of each image, e.g. `pause.png`
  for img in $(ls $1); do
    # Check if any of the files mention the image filename
    if ! grep -qR $img *; then
      rm $1$img
    fi
  done
}

# Recursively search for all directories named `imgs` or `images`
# All of the image directories use one of these two names
for dir in $(ls -d -R */*im[ag][gs]*/); do
  search $dir
done
```

Executed from `/src/content/en/tools/chrome-devtools/`.

I then ran a local server, and checked each page with DevTools open. DevTools didn't produce any 404s so I'm reasonably confident that the script worked as intended

Produces a 9M reduction in the directory size. I was hoping for more, but hey, every bit counts. Removing all those unused files should help reduce cognitive burden for docs maintainers, too

pull_request_body:
@petele check this out

My goal is to create a reusable feedback widget that I can inline at the end of DevTools tutorial sections. This will give me much more granular information about where exactly people are failing.

I've put the widget inside of a framebox because I want to disable the buttons after the user clicks one of them, as a means of preventing them from clicking both buttons and distorting the data.

I made it pretty customizable, because I think it'll get boring if the success and response items say the same thing every time. Switching up the button / response texts should help keep the user engaged and participating.

When I run this on the local server, the `{% setvar %}` tags aren't working properly, but I think I'm doing it correctly. See #4041 

Ditto for the framebox. I think I'm doing that one correctly, too, though. I think the local server just isn't set up to support these features

Given this, I'm not sure if the widget is going to display correctly. If this pattern looks OK to you, we can just check it when it's on staging

Note: I also moved some common styles to another file and removed some comments. These aren't related to the feedback widget
petele_commented_str:
Overall - love the idea, let's make it happen!

I think we can simplify the implementation, especially given the fact a lot of this is in a framebox, but we might even be able to simplify that too. I'll put time on your calendar to discuss further.

I've put in a few comments from my experimenting, mostly as an FYI.

pull_request_title: Extend the tags system for /updates/ to work for /showcase/
pull_request_body:
We would like the ability to link to WebVR specific showcases from the WebVR section of fundamentals.

To that end I have extended the `tags` feature of `/updates/` so that it will work for `/showcase/` too.

Actual showcases with the `webvr` tag are still incoming, but for testing you can add `{# wf_tags: webvr #}` (or whatever tags you like) to random case studies and rebuild.

R: @petele @PaulKinlan 

@meganlindsay: FYI. The resulting pages will be just like https://developers.google.com/web/updates/tags/chrome55 only they will say "Showcases" instead of "Updates" at the top.

SWEET! This is awesome.

Couple of small changes:

1) Instead of keeping a separate set of templates for updates and showcase, can we just use the same ones and move them out of the `src/templates/updates` directory?
2) Add the tags yaml file to the _book.yaml in showcase, the same way it is in updates.

pull_request_title: Clarify promise usage in service worker example
pull_request_body:
This change makes the use of promises in the code example clear, and safe when people copy-paste.

A lot of readers will be unclear about the important differences between `registration.then(mapSuccess, mapError)` and `registration.then(mapSuccess).catch(mapError)`, namely that in the second example `mapError` handles both registration errors *and* errors from the `mapSuccess` handler.

This change makes the comment `// registration failed :(` true regardless of changes made to the currently safe `mapSuccess` function. The error handler will now indeed run if-and-only-if the registration itself fails.

This was a doozy\r\n\r\nThe new doc is [index.md](https://github.com/google/WebFundamentals/compare/master...kaycebasques:cdt-perf?expand=1#diff-dd6e42295cd623684916dbe974b717b7)... in my preview GitHub isn't loading large diffs by default anymore

pull_request_title: Add markups to support RTL languages (fixes #4539)
pull_request_body:
Related issue: #4539 

This solution is based on W3C articles:

1. [Creating HTML Pages in Arabic, Hebrew and Other Right-to-left Scripts (tutorial)](https://www.w3.org/International/tutorials/bidi-xhtml)
2. [Structural markup and right-to-left text in HTML](https://www.w3.org/International/articles/inline-bidi-markup/uba-basics)

There're other articles from W3C to read about this, but I'm tired & busy to read them now and wanted to share what I have with you. Maybe someone could see this fix as an appropriate fix and add to it. Or, it could be inapplicable for the project and I should stop!

Known issues:
1. no margins in the right toc.
2. In RTL languages (tested with Arabic), lines with English text only flow from RTL! (Could be fixed by wrapping it with `<bdi>` or `<span>`, didn't test but should work. Or add `dir=auto` to every paragraph!
3. English-only headings are from RTL in RTL languages. Either it should be translated or wrapped with `<bdi>` / span

I just test Arabic and English text which look fine to me. Maybe other languages need extra treatments...

Suggested reviewers:
@PaulKinlan, @samdutton, @petele, @ianbarber (because you were involved with localisation & RTL issues)
Episode 5 going out today
Removed apostrophe in PWAs
R: anyone

`exec()` spawns a shell, which means that unsanitised user input must not be passed. The example suggests doing exactly that. Presumably people will use Lighthouse, but nevertheless I don't think such a potentially dangerous approach should be shown as an example.\r\n\r\nThis commit changes the example to use `execFile()`. This does not spawn a shell, avoiding the security risks of `exec()`.

pull_request_body:
Hey @petele check it out:

* by storing the question / response data in JSON and populating the framebox with a little JS, we can support questions with any number of choices. see [evaluate-performance/index.md](https://github.com/google/WebFundamentals/compare/master...kaycebasques:wf-multichoicefeedback?expand=1#diff-dd6e42295cd623684916dbe974b717b7) for an example of a question with three choices (v1 of the widget is hard-coded to only support two choices)
* this refactor can also replace the v1 widget. it handles all of v1's features 100%. see [javascript/index.md](https://github.com/google/WebFundamentals/compare/master...kaycebasques:wf-multichoicefeedback?expand=1#diff-f755648971e7f7ec554c20e5ff5454cd) for example
* I like that I can include the JSON directly in the page. In v1 there's too much indirection and it's tedious to author
* I like the flexibility of a JS solution

In general I'm very happy with this new workflow. Let me know if you're cool with it
cc @PaulKinlan @owencm

pull_request_body:
Pulled out the right image names from English version and replaced them with Bash script in pt-br, ko, id, es and zh-ch.

Script:
```
#!/bin/bash

for URL in src/content/pt-br/fundamentals/getting-started/codelabs/push-notifications/index.md src/content/ko/fundamentals/getting-started/codelabs/push-notifications/index.md src/content/id/fundamentals/getting-started/codelabs/push-notifications/index.md src/content/es/fundamentals/getting-started/codelabs/push-notifications/index.md src/content/zh-cn/fundamentals/getting-started/codelabs/push-notifications/index.md
do
	sed -i -e 's/49b343a07e2c92d.png/4525ec369fc2ae47.png/g' $URL
	sed -i -e 's/d670cb813f3a7575.png/6b698d7c7bbf1bc0.png/g' $URL
	sed -i -e 's/d712c8726928ca4.png/de3ceca91043d278.png/g' $URL
	sed -i -e 's/b9787463acb7e3fb.png/15f6375617c11974.png/g' $URL
	sed -i -e 's/5b8a7e9905f2237b.png/227cea0abe03a5b4.png/g' $URL
	sed -i -e 's/bfdc9f92e001934a.png/8fe2b1b110f87b34.png/g' $URL
	sed -i -e 's/c69f7428408c5bbc.png/8775071d7fd66432.png/g' $URL
	sed -i -e 's/e36f921fa7598419.png/2b5314607196f4e1.png/g' $URL
	sed -i -e 's/c0fab1022906d01f.png/2b089bdf10a8a945.png/g' $URL
	sed -i -e 's/cb84e05044ad029f.png/cf0e71f76cb79cc4.png/g' $URL
	sed -i -e 's/e320ddd1b66682e6.png/a12fbfdc08233592.png/g' $URL
	sed -i -e 's/3c5c0d5d1c3deda4.png/2973c2b818ca9324.png/g' $URL
	sed -i -e 's/fdedaa6d10e2f43e.png/75b1fedbfb7e0b99.png/g' $URL
	sed -i -e 's/32acb7ec17ef75a8.png/33dd89c437c17c97.png/g' $URL
done

```
